<subSubSection id="C4418B4A201BE0F606C6A85037A87058" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="96B51B400B639508FC84CA2790C3B88B" pageId="0" pageNumber="169">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7348F44FB7D89B609106A4382391EB83" pageId="0" pageNumber="169">
The specific epithet is a reference to the close similarity of the new species to 
<taxonomicName id="B9AC997FF9FB015A2F11D8986216C996" authorityName="RJ Blahnik" authorityYear="2002" class="Insecta" family="Philopotamidae" genus="Chimarra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Chimarra (Otarrha) odonta" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="169" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="odonta" subGenus="Otarrha">Chimarra (Otarrha) odonta</taxonomicName>
. Derived from the Greek, &quot; 
<emphasis id="AB8B7F007D4A468C1581830AAE081D72" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="169">para</emphasis>
&quot; = beside or near.
</paragraph>
